{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01ACJFBJEe96oLb7k417JNBy","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The admission webhook for the ingress-nginx controller is blocking this. Even with `allow-snippet-annotations: \"true\"` in the ConfigMap, the webhook is denying it with \"risky annotation\". \n\nIn newer ingress-nginx versions (1.9.0+), there's a concept of \"risky annotations\" that are blocked by the admission webhook regardless of `allow-snippet-annotations`. The webhook validates based on ingress-specific configuration in the `spec.controller` setting.\n\nLet me try a different approach. Instead of using configuration-snippet, I'll:\n\n**Option 1: Modify the Elasticsearch ConfigMap to disable security**\nThis is the cleanest path forward since the test case expects security to be disabled anyway. I need to check if the pods will restart cleanly when I change these settings. Looking at the current StatefulSet, there's an init container that copies certificates to an emptyDir volume, and the main container mounts those certs and references them in the config. If I disable `xpack.security.enabled`, those certificate references would become unnecessary, but I need to make sure the pod startup doesn't fail when it can't find the cert files.\n\nThe safest approach is to completely replace the ConfigMap with the intended configuration—security disabled and transport TLS disabled—then roll out the StatefulSet. When security is disabled in Elasticsearch 7.x, the transport SSL settings are ignored anyway, so I should remove them entirely to avoid any potential conflicts or startup errors. Updating the ConfigMap...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":221,"cache_read_input_tokens":55878,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":221},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standa